{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17474768","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17474768"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:24:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:24:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12392"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12392","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12392"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.05,0.02,0.67,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4902"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46502"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4902","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4902"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12392"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31414"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"882"},{"type":"tags","id":"2210"},{"type":"tags","id":"4208"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7988"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8008"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46502","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/46502"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThis photograph was taken after the birth of this infant (Image). The defect had been identified on prenatal ultrasonography and the family counselled that the pregnancy should be allowed to continue, with a natural delivery. The baby is otherwise healthy, with stable vital signs and no other congenital anomalies.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Gastroschisis","Umbilical hernia","Urachal cyst","Omphalocele","Umbilical granuloma"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is an \u003Cstrong\u003Eomphalocele\u003C/strong\u003E (exomphalos). In this congenital defect there is a protrusion of abdominal contents through a defect in the anterior abdominal wall and these are covered by a sac. The sac may sometimes rupture during delivery. The umbilical cord is usually attached to the summit of the sac.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Egastroschisis\u003C/strong\u003E is a congenital defect in which the intestines protrude through a defect in the abdominal wall. The defect is most commonly located to the right of the umbilicus. The protruding viscus is not covered by a sac.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eumbilical hernia\u003C/strong\u003E is a protrusion of abdominal contents through a defect at the umbilicus and would be covered by skin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eurachal cyst\u003C/strong\u003E is a congenital abnormality that occurs when a small pouch, called the urachus, that connects the bladder to the umbilicus in a fetus, does not close properly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAn umbilical granuloma\u003C/strong\u003E is a benign lesion that can occur at the site of the umbilicus in newborns, but it is not associated with a protrusion of abdominal contents through a defect in the abdominal wall.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Omphalocele is a congenital defect in which the abdominal contents protrude through a defect in the anterior abdominal wall and is covered by a sac","Presence of the sac and the site of attachment of the umbilical cord to the sac help in distinction from gastroschisis."],"references":["https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK519010/","Verla MA, Style CA, Olutoye OO. Prenatal diagnosis and management of omphalocele. Semin Pediatr Surg 2019; 28:84-88"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31414"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12392"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18997"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18997","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18997"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9081491f-4c8d-4134-abba-795766749806.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9081491f-4c8d-4134-abba-795766749806.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":435}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31414","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/31414"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-06-05T17:56:11+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-06-05T17:56:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4902"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46502"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"up